[normal]David Prior[bold]: 
[normal]It is very much work in progress
[normal] at the moment.
[normal] As to the new hospital inspections we have started, we will have done 18 by Christmas and we will have published a shadow rating for three of them. An assessment of those 18 inspections will be very important. The question is, 
[normal]h
[normal]ave we got underneath the skin of these hospitals? Can we actually do an inspection 
[normal]that
[normal] can determine whether or not that hospital is safe, well led, 
[normal]of 
[normal]high quality and providing compassionate care?
[normal] 
[normal]I guess the jury is still out on that. 
[normal]I should say that
[normal],
[normal] as to the ones we have done so far
[normal],
[normal] we have had between 25 and 30 people on the inspection team, a large preponderance of clinicians and experts by experience as well as inspectors
[normal], and 
[normal]Mike Richards
[normal]’
[normal] view is that we are getting underneath the skin of those 
[normal]hospitals, finding out what is happening and getting a real understanding of what is going on in them. If we can do that and hold it up as an accurate mirror to the public, commissioners and to other hospitals, that will be one marker in the ground in the hospital sector of what is good. It will not pick up everything. We are not going to pick up everything in a hospital. 
[normal]To give you an idea of the size of it, 
[normal]Barts
[normal] has revenues of £1 billion, employs 15,000 people and is on five different big hospital sites. We are not going to pick up everything in every ward, department and specialty, but we do feel that we will pick up systemic problems in those hospitals. So
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]n the hospital sector
[normal],
[normal] the honest answer to the question is that it is too early to say, but 
[normal]that
[normal] is critical to me
[normal]. A
